        Selling in Bowen Hills 2026
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(25,24,23,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Bowen Hills has evolved from a transitional precinct to an established inner-city address. Here is what sellers need to know about the apartment-led market in 2026.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Bowen Hills occupies a position in Brisbane's inner-north that has transformed significantly over the past decade. The suburb's anchor institutions, the RNA Showgrounds, the Bowen Hills train station, the Royal Brisbane and Women's Hospital to the north, and the King Street mixed-use precinct, have drawn consistent development activity that has repositioned it from an industrial-fringe address to a recognised inner-city neighbourhood. Sellers in Bowen Hills are operating in a market where building selection and the quality of disclosure matter enormously, because buyers here are sophisticated and do thorough pre-purchase research.</p>

      <p>The Bowen Hills property market is predominantly apartments. The detached cottage market on a handful of elevated streets is thin and low-turnover, and most sellers are dealing with either mid-rise or high-rise residential stock. That context shapes everything about how a sale should be run: the body corporate disclosure, the sinking fund status, the quality of the building's management, and the rental yield if the property has been an investment all come under scrutiny in a way they do not in the detached home market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Bowen Hills</h2>
      <p>The Bowen Hills buyer pool is more varied than most inner-city apartment suburbs. Owner-occupier professionals who want inner-city access without CBD rents make up one strong segment, and the King Street precinct's ground-floor retail and dining has given that buyer a reason to see Bowen Hills as a genuine lifestyle address rather than just a convenient commuter suburb. A second significant segment is the investor looking at yield and medium-term capital growth, drawn by proximity to RBWH, the university of Queensland's Herston campus, and the upcoming Cross River Rail station. The third is the downsizer from a Brisbane outer-suburb family home who wants low-maintenance living with city access.</p>

      <p>Building age is the most significant variable in which segment a property attracts. Stock built in the last decade, particularly around the King Street precinct, attracts the owner-occupier and active investor. Older 1990s and early 2000s buildings attract a more yield-focused investor base, and sometimes buyers who have been priced out of newer stock and are willing to accept lower amenity for position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Bowen Hills</h2>
      <p>Building management quality is the single largest value driver in an apartment-led market like Bowen Hills. A well-managed building with a healthy sinking fund and no pending special levies trades at a clear premium to a building with deferred maintenance and a depleted fund. Buyers ask for body corporate records as standard and a building that presents clean records will attract more bidders and stronger offers.</p>

      <p>Position within the building matters almost as much as the building itself. High-floor apartments with north or east-facing aspects and city or showgrounds views have historically commanded premiums that ground-floor or south-facing stock cannot match. Proximity to the King Street precinct at street level adds a lifestyle dimension that resonates with owner-occupier buyers. Any parking situation, number of spaces, visitor access, storage allocation, should be documented and disclosed clearly before campaign launch.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Bowen Hills property for sale</h2>
      <p>In Bowen Hills, preparation is primarily about disclosure rather than presentation. Gather body corporate records, the latest administrative and sinking fund levies, the sinking fund forecast report, meeting minutes for the past two years, and any correspondence about maintenance or building issues. Buyers will request these during due diligence and any gap in the record will slow the process and give buyers negotiating use. The property itself should be clean, freshly painted if needed, and photographed professionally. Natural light and view direction are the most marketable visual assets in apartment photography.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Bowen Hills</h2>
      <p>Bowen Hills does not follow the seasonal family buyer calendar as strongly as suburban family markets. The professional and investor buyer segments are active year-round, with demand connected to hospital employment cycles, university semesters and broader investment market conditions rather than school term rhythms. The two windows that consistently produce stronger buyer competition are the late February to May autumn period, when professional buyers who have settled into new jobs or contracts from the start of year are actively purchasing, and the September to November spring period, which generates the highest volumes of open home attendance across all Brisbane markets. The Cross River Rail connection, when it opens, is expected to create an additional demand catalyst that will support Bowen Hills values regardless of season.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Bowen Hills</h2>
      <p>Well-presented Bowen Hills apartments have been selling within 35 to 60 days, reflecting the time buyers need to complete body corporate due diligence alongside standard building and pest and finance conditions. The range is wider than detached home markets because the quality and condition of the building, not just the apartment, heavily influences buyer confidence. Stock in newer, well-managed buildings in the King Street precinct moves at the faster end of that range. Older buildings with pending maintenance or less transparent records take longer and sometimes require more active price negotiation. The investor buyer can move faster than the owner-occupier when yield and location align, and that segment has been one of the most active in inner-Brisbane apartment markets through 2025 and into 2026.</p>

